anings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Osborne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Osborne","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osbern</i>, partly from late Old English <i>Ōsbern</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Ásbiǫrn</i> (from <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>biǫrn</i> ‘bear’), but more usually from Norman use of the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Ōsbern</i>. <i>Osbern</i> was often treated as an alternative form of <i>Osbert</i>. For pet forms see   Hoskin   and   Opie  . The surname has also been established in Ireland (Waterford, Tipperary) since the mid 16th century."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Osburn Baron of Sitting Bourne was born in 1320, in Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Thomas Osborne, was 20 and his mother, Mary Robson, was 17. He married Lady John Osborne in 1339, in Hartlip, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1380, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1320–1380":"1320–1380","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1340–1404":"1340–1404","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1404":"1404","1304":"1304","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1380":"1380","1339":"1339","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Hartlip Swale Cliff Kent England":"Hartlip, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sittingbourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Sittingbourne, Kent, England":"Sittingbourne, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1320–1380":"1320–1380","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1340–1404":"1340–1404","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1304–Female":"1304–Kuollut","1404":"1404","1304":"1304","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1380":"1380","1339":"1339","about 1340":"noin 1340","Hartlip Swale Cliff Kent England":"Hartlip, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sittingbourne, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Sittingbourne, Kent, England":"Sittingbourne, Kent, England"},"fr":{"1320–1380":"1320–1380","1320–Female":"1320–Décédée","1340–1404":"1340–1404","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1304–Female":"1304–Décédée","1404":"1404","1304":"1304","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1380":"1380","1339":"1339","about 1340":"environ 1340","Hartlip Swale Cliff Kent England":"Hartlip, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Sittingbourne, Kent, England, Unite